    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Largish perennial plant with elongate, soft, quill-like green leaves that lie prostrate on the sand and are covered with papery brown sheaths at their bases. The stout, upright, tree-like, branching flower head bears small nodding white, aromatic flowers from July to October.&nbsp; Petals of flowers are strongly curled backwards and only a few of the flowers on the head open each day.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9861",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Leaves up to 1m long.<i> </i>Flower head up to about 50 cm tall. Leaves about 5 cm diameter, Flowers 2.5 cm across.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9862",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to Southern Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Southern Namibia to Eastern Cape. Introduced to Australia where it is considered a weed.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9863",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Very common species on coastal dunes, where it is sometimes a dominant plant. An edible species that has several uses - the buds and leaves can be eaten and the sap has been used in traditional medicine as a lotion for sores. There is current interest is re-establishing the species as a wild vegetable.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9864",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9865",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers July to ~October.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9866",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>This is a diverse genus with about 50 regional species of which 24 occur in the fynbos biome. This species can be confused with the Cape spinach <i>T. ciliata</i>, which as a similar distribution and coastal habitat, but that species has flowers that do not curl backwards and are borne closely-packed along a single long spike, opening sequentially from the bottom of the spike. Namaqualand wild cabbage <i>T. falcata</i> is restricted to the west coast and has just a few, broader, lance-shaped leaves and an upright flower spike with just a couple of parallel branches.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9867",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
